Incident.Summary: Single motor vehicle accident resulting in a DUI arrest.

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText:
Maryland State Police Annapolis Barrack.

Body-worn camera operational and in-car camera J-8 operational.

Defendant: Francis Bernard Walsh 3rd

Date of Birth: 08/10/1965

Date of Incident: 06/06/2023

Time of Incident: 0110

Maryland Driver's License: W-420-261-085-625

DUI# J-23-101


Training and Certification:

*I am trained by the Maryland State Police and the National Highway Transportation Safety Administration to administer Standardized Field Sobriety Tests.

*I am a certified Preliminary Breath Test operator.


VEHICLE IN MOTION (PHASE 1)

On June 5th, 2023, at approximately 2315 hours (11:15 PM), I, Trooper Baker #7430, was dispatched to a single-vehicle collision. The location of the accident was on southbound Roscoe Rowe Blvd prior to Kirkley Road. Prior to my arrival Cpl. Anderson #6354 advised the driver of the vehicle was the registered owner, who was later identified by his Maryland Driver's License as Francis Bernard Walsh 3rd (W/M DOB: 08/10/1965). Before my arrival, Walsh was ground transported by Anne Arundel County Fire Department (EMS Run #2023-39165) and was en route to the University of Maryland Shock Trauma Center for the injuries suffered in the accident. 

I arrived on the scene at 2323 hours (11:23 AM) and observed a navy blue Jeep Compass displaying Maryland Registration "2DT6580". The Jeep was located off the road, on the left side, by a tree. The Jeep had heavy front-end damage, deployed airbags all around, a cracked front windshield, and damage to the front driver/passenger side door. I concluded from my accident investigation that the Jeep was on US-50 and took the eastbound ramp to Roscoe Rowe Blvd. While on the ramp, the Jeep struck the guardrail on its left side. Damage was found on the guardrail and skid marks on the roadway. After striking the guardrail, the Jeep ran off the road left through the grass, and crossed lanes one and two on Roscoe Rowe Blvd. A tire trail was found in the grass. The Jeep struck the curb, ran off the road left into the grass, and struck tree branches. Black marks were found on the curb and tire marks in the grass leading up to the tree branches where the Jeep was found. 

One clear metal tube with a lighter and a "Chore Boy" scrubber was located on the driver's side floorboard. On the driver's side seat was one plastic bag with specs of a white substance. The plastic bag had no evidentiary value and was unable to be tested. One unopened pint-size fireball containing alcohol was found underneath the passenger seat. The passenger side door was wet from a liquid and had the moderate odor of an alcoholic beverage. 

After observing everything found in the vehicle and with my training, knowledge, and experience with prior CDS-related arrested and DUI-related arrests, I believed criminal activity occurred. 

Troopers on the scene waited for the vehicle to be towed. I left the scene to obtain paperwork/blood kit from the Maryland State Police Annapolis Barrack and was then en route to shock trauma to make contact with Walsh.


PERSONAL CONTACT:

I arrived at Shock Trauma at approximately 0046 hrs (12:46 AM) and subsequently made contact with Walsh. Walsh appeared to have a cut on his face and a hurt neck. Walsh advised he was at an AA meeting earlier and was headed home to his residence. Walsh was asked what happened tonight during the accident, and Walsh advised he wasn't sure. Walsh advised he thought he was on Riva Road and remembered losing control of the vehicle. Walsh appeared to have a difficult time remembering the events of the accident. 

Walsh advised he had one Steel Reserve 24 oz alcoholic drink and one Milwaukee beer 24 oz alcohol drink approximately 15 to 20 minutes before he started driving. Walsh advised he smoked crack cocaine in the woods off of West Street with some friends about 2 hours before driving. Walsh was asked if there was any crack inside his vehicle, and Walsh advised he wished there was. 

While speaking to Walsh, I observed Walsh to have slowed and slurred speech. Walsh appeared to have glassy eyes, and I could smell the moderate odor of an alcoholic beverage emanating from Walsh's breath. 

Walsh repeatedly advised he was sorry and that he messed up tonight. 

I asked Walsh the following questions: 

Medical Conditions – No.

Physical Disabilities - No.

Medication – No.

ARREST:

Based on the following, I had reason to believe that Walsh was driving under the influence of drugs and alcohol.

*Moderate odor of an alcoholic beverage emitting from the vehicle's front passenger side door. Walsh was the only occupant inside the vehicle. 

*Items found inside the vehicle associated with the use of crack cocaine. 

*Moderate odor of an alcoholic beverage emitting from Walsh's breath.

*Slurred and slowed speech.

*Glassy eyes.

*Admission to consuming an alcoholic drink.

*Admission to smoking crack cocaine. 

*Single-vehicle collision. 

*Repetitive story.
 

Given the aforementioned observations, I determined Walsh could not have operated a motor vehicle safely. 
 

The DR-15 Advice of Rights was read to Walsh in English. At the conclusion of the DR-15, Walsh elected to submit to a blood test for alcohol/controlled dangerous substance (CDS) at 0123 hours (1:23 AM). Walsh signed the DR-15.
 

Walsh's blood was drawn utilizing blood kit J-85. The blood was drawn by Amanda Maltingly, a nurse, on June 6th, 2023, at 0127 hours (1:27 AM). I transported and submitted the blood kit to the Maryland State Police Chemical Test for Alcohol Unit for testing. 
 

All appropriate paperwork was explained and provided to Walsh. Walsh was subsequently released into the hospital's custody. 
 

All events occurred in Anne Arundel County and Baltimore City.
 

I request this case remain open pending the results of the blood analysis test.

On June 5, 2023, at approximately 2247 hours, I was on routine patrol in the uniform of the day in unmarked Maryland State Police vehicle J-16. At that time, I was northbound on Rowe Blvd prior to the ramp to eastbound Rt. 50 when I observed dust and smoke in the center median. I then observed headlights in the center median, at which time I was able to observe there was a collision with airbags deployed throughout the vehicle. I made a U-turn at Rt. 50 and pulled up to the scene and immediately started additional units and Fire/EMS. I exited my patrol vehicle and went up to the vehicle, which was observed to be a black Jeep bearing Maryland Registration 2DT6580. Due to the airbag deployment, I was not able to see inside the vehicle, so I opened the door and yelled into the vehicle, at which time I heard someone in the vehicle still. I cut back the driver's side airbag and I saw the driver and sole occupant of the vehicle laying across the driver and passenger seat. He was responsive and I noticed there was a gash near his right eye and I observed blood dripping onto the passenger side floor board. At that time, I told the driver to remain how he was, and I went back to my patrol car to get my medical bag. I pulled out a bandage wrap and told the driver to hold pressure on the wound. I then found a medium-sized gauze pad and then had the driver hold pressure with that as well.

     EMS arrived on-scene and after their assessment, they determined the driver had possible life-threatening injuries, and they stated they would be flying the driver out. They then cancelled the helicopter and drove priority to Baltimore Shock Trauma. Anne Arundel Police followed the Medic Unit to Shock Trauma. Anne Arundel County Police initially started the investigation, revealing the driver's identity as Francis Bernard Walsh 3rd, W/M, DOB: 8/10/1965. He was identified by his Maryland Driver's License. As Anne Arundel County Police began their investigation, they noticed evidence that Walsh lost control of his vehicle on the ramp from eastbound Rt. 50 to southbound Rowe Blvd. It appeared Walsh grazed the guard rail on the ramp, then went through the median between the ramp and Rowe Blvd before jumping up a curb and striking a tree head on. Night shift units responded and Tpr, Baker #7430 assumed the investigation.

All events occurred in Anne Arundel County, Maryland.

On September 4, 2023, I was provided with blood kit results from the MSP Forensic Science Division. The test results for Walsh's blood specimen revealed an alcohol concentration of 0.16. On September 5, 2023, at approximately 1930 hours, I met Walsh at the MSP Annapolis Barrack front lobby. Walsh was informed of his blood kit results, and citations were issued. Walsh's Maryland Drivers License was confiscated, and a DR-15A was issued. Walsh was given an additional DR-15 along with paperwork regarding the blood kit. Walsh signed all appropriate documents. I explained all the paperwork given to Walsh.

  All events occurred in Anne Arundel County, MD.

  I request this case be closed.
